Here we will use SVM implementation available in the library e1071 to fit classifiers with linear and radial (polynomial for extra points) kernels and to compare their relative performances; we will also compare their performance to that of random forest and KNN.

Problem 1 (20 points): support vector classifier (i.e.using linear kernel)

  • Use svm() function from library e1071 with kernel="linear" to fit classifier (see e.g.ISLR Ch.9.6.1) to the entire WiFi localization dataset setting parameter cost to 0.001, 1, 1000 and 1 mln.
for (c in c(0.001, 1, 1000, 1e6)){
svmres = svm(Loc3 ~ ., data = wifiLocDat, kernel = 'linear', cost = c)
print(paste0("Cost = ", c, ", Number of Support Vectors:", svmres$tot.nSV))
}
## [1] "Cost = 0.001, Number of Support Vectors:1013"
## [1] "Cost = 1, Number of Support Vectors:1000"
## [1] "Cost = 1000, Number of Support Vectors:1015"
## [1] "Cost = 1e+06, Number of Support Vectors:450"
  • Describe how those changes in the cost parameter affect (1) the model fitting process (hint: the difficulty of the underlying optimization problem increases with cost can you explain why?) and (2) its outcome (e.g.how does the number of support vectors change with cost?). What are the implications?

As the cost parameter increases, the model is fit with a narrower margin. Between cost = 0.001 and 1000, this did not result in a very large difference in the number of support vectors. However, when the cost was increased to 1e6, the number of support vectors decreased significantly.

  • Please explain explicitly (ever so briefly is fine) why the change in cost value impacts number of support vectors found. (hint: there is an answer in ISLR.)

The cost value represents the cost of a violation to the margin, so a larger cost value corresponds with a narrower margin and a smaller cost value corresponds with a wider margin. A wider margin results in more support vectors.

  • Use tune() function from library e1071 (see ISLR Ch.9.6.1 for details and examples of usage) to determine approximate value of the cost that yields the lowest error in cross-validation employed by tune. Please use the grid for the cost parameter spanning the range between 0.1 and 100. Note that for the cost range spanning orders of magnitude it would be a good idea to use (approximately) logarithmic grid density e.g.something like 0.1, 0.3, 1, 3, 10, or 0.1, 0.2, 0.5, 1, etc.). When you find the (approximately) optimal cost, you may rerun tune() on a denser grid just around that value to get a more accurate result (for your own enjoyment, this is not required).
tune = tune(svm, Loc3 ~ ., data = wifiLocDat, kernel = 'linear', 
            ranges = list(cost = c(0.1, 0.3, 1, 3, 10, 30, 100)))
summary(tune)

  • Now setup a resampling procedure by repeatedly splitting the entire dataset into training and test subsets. In each resampling iteration (1) use just the training subset to fully tune cost value (in other words, we are now asking tune to perform all of its own crossvalidation splits and to identify the best cost parameter value using training data only); then (2) use the test subset (i.e.the part of the data that was truly unseen before, not even for choosing the models hyperparameter cost in this case) to estimate the classification test error of the best model tuned on the training subset. Draw distributions of the test errors (boxplots are fine) reported by tune for the best models (i.e.obtained through cross-validation on the training set) and those computed for the selected best model on the actual test set, discuss.
par(mfrow = c(3, 3))
for (t in 1:9){
sample = sample(c(TRUE, FALSE), nrow(wifiLocDat), replace = TRUE, prob = c(0.7, 0.3)) #70/30 split

train = wifiLocDat[sample, ]
test = wifiLocDat[-sample, ]

tunecv = tune(svm, Loc3 ~ ., data = train, kernel = 'linear', 
            ranges = list(cost = c(0.1, 0.3, 1, 3, 10, 30, 100)))

bestm = tunecv$best.model
pred = predict(bestm, newdata = test)

conf = confusionMatrix(pred, test$Loc3)

testerr = 1 - conf$overall[1]

boxplot(tunecv$performances$error, main = paste0("Training Error ", t, "\nBest Cost: ", tunecv$best.parameters), ylim = c(0.21, 0.26))
abline(h = testerr, col = 'blue')
legend(legend = c('test'), fill = 'blue', "topright")

}

With 9 resamplings, the training error for each set is between 0.21 and 0.26. The range in error is narrow across the different cost values. The testing error is below the training error in 5 of the sets and above for 4. The most frequent best cost parameter is 1, which was chosen 4 times. Next was 30, which was chosen twice. 0.1 , 3, and 10 were each chosen once.

Problem 2 (10 points): comparison to random forest

  • Fit random forest classifier on the entire WiFi localization dataset using default parameters.
rf = randomForest(Loc3 ~ ., wifiLocDat)
rf

##       FALSE TRUE class.error

## TRUE     12  488  0.02400000

  • Obtain resulting misclassification error as reported by the confusion matrix in random forest output.

  • Explain why error reported in random forest confusion matrix represents estimated test (as opposed to train) error of the procedure.

Random forest reports out-of-bag error, which uses the subset of data that was not used in fitting the model. The dataset for the bagged tree is like the training set and then the out-of-bag error is like the testing set.

  • Compare resulting test error to that for support vector classifier obtained above and discuss results of such comparison.

The test error for the support vector classifier above was 0.2, which is over 10-fold higher than the error for random forest, which was 0.0135.

For this problem, there is no need to set up an external resampling loop, you can use the whole dataset.

Problem 3 (10 points): Comparison to cross-validation tuned KNN predictor

  • Use convenience wrapper tune.knn provided by the library e1071 on the entire dataset to determine optimal value for the number of the nearest neighbors k to be used in KNN classifier. Consider our observations from week 10 problem set when choosing range of values of k to be evaluated by tune.knn.
knntn = tune.knn(y = wifiLocDat$Loc3, x = wifiLocDat[1:7], data = wifiLocDat, k = c(1, 3, 5, 10, 20, 50, 100))

  • Then setup a hierachical resampling procedure similar to the one used in Problem 1 for support vector classifier: the procedure will repeatedly (1) split WiFi localization dataset into training and test; (2) use tune.knn on just the training data to determine optimal k; and then (3) use k estimated by tune.knn from the training subset to make KNN classifications on the test subset. Report and discuss distributions of test errors from this procedure, as well as the distributions of the selected values of k (since we are now tuning on a new, randomly selected training subset every time, the selected best values for \(k\) might be different!). Compare the test errors to those obtained earlier when using random forest and support vector classifier.
par(mfrow = c(3, 3))
for (t in 1:9){
sample = sample(c(TRUE, FALSE), nrow(wifiLocDat), replace = TRUE, prob = c(0.7, 0.3)) #70/30 split


train = wifiLocDat[sample, ]
test = wifiLocDat[-sample, ]

train$Loc3 = as.numeric(train$Loc3) #convert to numeric to avoid knn error
test$Loc3 = as.numeric(test$Loc3)

knncv = tune.knn(y = wifiLocDat$Loc3, x = wifiLocDat[1:7], data = wifiLocDat, k = c(1, 3, 5, 10, 20, 50, 100))

bestm = knncv$best.model
bestk = bestm$k
pred = knn(train = train, test = test, k = bestk, cl = train$Loc3)

conf = confusionMatrix(as.factor(pred), as.factor(test$Loc3))

testerr = 1 - conf$overall[1]

boxplot(knncv$performances$error, main = paste0("Training Error ", t, "\nBest K: ", knncv$best.parameters), ylim = c(0, 0.022))
abline(h = testerr, col = 'green4')
legend(legend = c('test'), fill = 'green4', "topright")

}

In 9 resampling sets, the best k value was 1 for 5 of them and 3 for the other 4. The training error is between 0.01 and 0.02, and the range in error between the different k values is larger than the range seen above with the different SVM costs. Testing error is lower than training error every time, ranging from around 0.002 to 0.009. KNN testing error is lower than SVM error and random forest error.

Problem 4 (20 points): SVM with radial kernel

Sub-problem 4a (10 points): impact of rate parameter \(\gamma\) on classification surface

  • Plot SVM model fit to the WiFi localization dataset using (for the ease of plotting) only the first and the second attributes as predictor variables, kernel="radial", cost=10 and gamma=5 (see ISLR Ch.9.6.2 for an example of that done with a simulated dataset).
radsvm = svm(Loc3 ~ WiFi1 + WiFi2, data = wifiLocDat, kernel = 'radial', cost = 10, gamma = 5)
summary(radsvm)
## 
## Call:
## svm(formula = Loc3 ~ WiFi1 + WiFi2, data = wifiLocDat, kernel = "radial", 
##     cost = 10, gamma = 5)
## 
## 
## Parameters:
##    SVM-Type:  C-classification 
##  SVM-Kernel:  radial 
##        cost:  10 
## 
## Number of Support Vectors:  294
## 
##  ( 173 121 )
## 
## 
## Number of Classes:  2 
## 
## Levels: 
##  FALSE TRUE
plot(radsvm, wifiLocDat, WiFi2 ~ WiFi1)

In the resulting plot, you should be able to see the yellow and brown regions separated by the classification boundary as computed by this model.

  • Also produce the same kinds of plots using 0.5 and 50 as the values for gamma. Compare classification boundaries in these three plots and describe how they are impacted by the change in the value of gamma.
    Can you trace it back to the role of the parameter gamma in the equation for the radial kernel in ISLR?
for (g in c(0.5, 50)){
radsvm = svm(Loc3 ~ WiFi1 + WiFi2, data = wifiLocDat, kernel = 'radial', cost = 10, gamma = g)
plot(radsvm, wifiLocDat, WiFi2 ~ WiFi1)
}

The boundary for classification = TRUE gets smaller as gamma increases. In the radial kernel equation, increasing gamma indicates that only very close points matter, resulting in the smaller boundary.

Sub-problem 4b (10 points): test error for SVM with radial kernel

  • In a way similar to how it was done earlier for the support vector classifier (and KNN), set up a resampling process that will repeatedly: (1) split the entire dataset (using all attributes as predictors) into training and test subsets; (2) in each iteration use tune function to determine the optimal values of cost and gamma; then (3) calculate the test error using these values of cost and gamma (on the actual test subset). Consider what you have learned above about the effects of the parameters cost and gamma to decide on the starting ranges of their values to be evaluated by tune.
par(mfrow = c(3, 3))
for (t in 1:9){
sample = sample(c(TRUE, FALSE), nrow(wifiLocDat), replace = TRUE, prob = c(0.7, 0.3)) #70/30 split

train = wifiLocDat[sample, ]
test = wifiLocDat[-sample, ]

tunecvr = tune(svm, Loc3 ~ ., data = train, kernel = 'radial', 
            ranges = list(cost = c(0.1, 0.3, 1, 3, 10, 30, 100), gamma = c(0.05, 1, 5, 10, 50)))

bestm = tunecvr$best.model
pred = predict(bestm, newdata = test)

conf = confusionMatrix(pred, test$Loc3)

testerr = 1 - conf$overall[1]

boxplot(tunecvr$performances$error, main = paste0("Training Error ", t, "\nBest Cost: ", tunecvr$best.parameters$cost, " Best Gamma: ", tunecvr$best.parameters$gamma ))
abline(h = testerr, col = 'orange')
legend(legend = c('test'), fill = 'orange', "topright")

}

  • Additionally, experiment with different sets of those values and discuss the results in your solution. Discuss how you would go about selecting the ranges for tuning starting from scratch.
par(mfrow = c(3, 3))
for (t in 1:9){
sample = sample(c(TRUE, FALSE), nrow(wifiLocDat), replace = TRUE, prob = c(0.7, 0.3)) #70/30 split

train = wifiLocDat[sample, ]
test = wifiLocDat[-sample, ]

tunecvr = tune(svm, Loc3 ~ ., data = train, kernel = 'radial', 
            ranges = list(cost = c(10, 20, 30, 40), gamma = c(0.01, 0.025, 0.05, 0.25, 0.5, 1, 1.5)))

bestm = tunecvr$best.model
pred = predict(bestm, newdata = test)

conf = confusionMatrix(pred, test$Loc3)

boxplot(tunecvr$performances$error, main = paste0("Training Error ", t, "\nBest Cost: ", tunecvr$best.parameters$cost, " Best Gamma: ", tunecvr$best.parameters$gamma ), ylim = c(0, 0.04))
abline(h = testerr, col = 'pink')
legend(legend = c('test'), fill = 'pink', "topright")

}

  • Present resulting test error graphically and compare them to those obtained in the previous problems with support vector classifier (i.e.with linear kernel), with random forest, and with KNN. Discuss results of these comparisons.

The original parameters resulted in much higher training error compared to the second set of radial kernel SVM training errors. The first set chose 0.05 gamma as the best 5 times and 1 gamma the otehr 4 times. In the second set, the training error was significantly lower. Best cost was 10 or 30, 3 times each. The most frequent gamma was 0.05 again, which was observed 4 times. Testing error was slightly higher than the KNN testing, lower than random forest error, and lower than the linear kernel SVM testing error.
